Content:
I would like to prove that the two algebras $\mathfrak{su}(2)$ and $\mathfrak{sl}(2,\mathbb R)$ are not isomorphic as Lie algebras. I started considering the following basis for $\mathfrak{su}(2)$ : \begin{equation}
\sigma_1=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
i &0\\
0 &-i\\
\end{pmatrix}
\quad
\sigma_2=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
0 &i\\
i &0\\
\end{pmatrix}
\quad
\sigma_3=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
0 &-1\\
1 &0\\
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation} and for $\mathfrak{sl}(2,\mathbb R)$ : \begin{equation}
A_1=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
1 &0\\
0 &-1\\
\end{pmatrix}
\quad
A_2=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
0 &1\\
0 &0\\
\end{pmatrix}
\quad
A_3=\frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix} 
0 &0\\
1 &0\\
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation} It is possible to check that for  the $\sigma$ s the following commutation relation holds: \begin{equation}
[\sigma_i,\sigma_j]=\epsilon_{ijk}\sigma_k.
\end{equation} While if we consider: \begin{equation}
[A_1,A_2]=A_2
\end{equation} Then it seems that I can't find any isomorphism between these 2 basis.
Now I would like to generalize the argument to every basis, does anyone have any idea on how to proceed?
